# Retail Sales & Customer Analytics Platform using Microsoft Fabric

The main goal of the project was to centralize sales, customer, inventory, and transaction data from multiple source systems into a unified Lakehouse architecture for near real-time analytics and reporting.
Basically, business teams were facing issues because data was spread across multiple systems, reporting was manual, and decision-making was taking more time.
So our objective was to build a scalable and centralized analytics platform using Microsoft Fabric.

Step 1 — Source Systems:
We received data from multiple source systems like:
> SQL Server
> REST APIs
> ERP systems
> CSV files
> Azure Blob Storage

For example:
> customer data came from SQL Server
> transaction data came from APIs
> inventory data came from ERP systems
> daily sales data came as CSV files

Step 2 — Data Ingestion:
For ingestion, we used:
 ---Microsoft Fabric Data Factory

We developed ETL/ELT pipelines to ingest both:
batch data
incremental data
into:
OneLake Bronze Layer
The Bronze layer stored raw data exactly as received from source systems for auditing and traceability purposes.

Step 3 — Data Transformation using PySpark:
After ingestion, I worked mainly on:

---PySpark notebooks in Microsoft Fabric
following:
 Medallion Architecture
with: > Bronze
      > Silver
      > Gold layers

Step 4 — Silver Layer Processing:
Then coming to the silver layer, In the Silver layer, we performed: > data cleansing
                                                                    > null handling
                                                                    > datatype standardization
                                                                    > deduplication
                                                                    > schema validation
                                                                    > business transformations
We also implemented:
INCREMENTAL LOADING
By using: > watermark logic
          > timestamp-based processing
so only newly arrived or modified records were processed instead of full reloads.
This reduced processing time and improved pipeline efficiency.

Step 5 — Gold Layer:
In the Gold layer, we created:
---business-ready curated datasets
for analytics and reporting.
And we designed STAR SCHEMA MODELS With : > Fact tables
                                          > dimension tables 
and implemented: SCD type 1 & SCD Type 2 for maintaining historical data changes.

Step 6 — Performance Optimization:
To improve Spark performance, we used: > partitioning
                                       > Caching
                                       >broadcast joins
This helped reduce shuffle operations and improved pipeline execution significantly.

Step 7 — Reporting & Analytics:
Finally, curated Gold layer data was connected to: POWER BI DASHBOARDS
 for : > saled and analysis
       > inventory analysis
       > customer insights
       > executive reporting
This enabled business users to make faster and data-driven decisions.

Step 8 — Security & Monitoring:
 For security: > RBAC policies were implemented
               > controlled access was provided across layers
We also performed: > data quality validations
                   > logging
                   > monitoring
                   > pipeline troubleshooting
----And finally, after completing the development and monitoring activities, we moved to deployment and environment migration.

Step 9 — Deployment:
For deployment and migration between: > DEV 
                                      > UAT 
                                      > Production
environments , we used : Git-based CI/CD pipelines
 for smooth release management and deployment automation
